\b\fs38 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Working Documents\
\pard\tx566\pardeftab720

\b0\fs32 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
As part of the submission of your project, you are required to submit a folio of working documents--this is in addition to your project report.\
\
The working documents should provide evidence (e.g. raw results, prototype code) of your experimental work, including implementation and evaluation and should include documents providing implementation information such as code listings, software designs, user questionnaires etc.\
\
The working documents should be viewable or downloadable via a web page.  (As mentioned above, the working documents need to be submitted electronically for plagiarism detection purposes along with the electronic version of the report.)  If you don't already have a web site, you can get one from ISS. See the following page for details: http://www.lancs.ac.uk/users/iss/registration/getapage.htm. You must use an official University web site so that we can be sure that your working documents remain available to us throughout the marking period.\
\
If you have a web page for your project already, just add the links to the code listings and any other information you think will be useful to us. And remember to specify the URL in the report. Remember, though, that the project is judged primarily on the report. All we require of the working documents pages is that they should be reasonably convenient for the markers of your research project to access. They needn't be aesthetic marvels--you shouldn't be spending lots of time making them pretty when you could be doing more important things, like polishing your report, getting your code to work, finishing your coursework, or revising for the exams.\
\
Again, note that the working documents web pages are a requirement of submission. Failure to make them available will result in a mark of 0 for your final year project.\
\
\pard\tx566\pardeftab720

\b\fs38 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
